<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">Two Miles West</DIV><br>
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<br /> 
‘Roses and lilies two miles west,’ <br /> 
said the red paint on whitewashed plank<br /> 
nailed to a burly trunk that sank <br /> 
like a drover on an ample breast. <br /> 
<br /> 
Once creaking oxcarts rolled this way <br /> 
over the wilderness of grass <br /> 
whose stems whispered ‘Alas, alas,’ <br /> 
as the plough cleft the virgin clay.<br />  
<br /> 
Where wayworn mothers came to nest<br />  
and chain clinked on the swingle ring,<br />  
what profit did the flowers bring? <br />  
‘Roses and lilies two miles west.’ <br /> 
<br><br>

<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('murphy')">by Tim Murphy</a></td></tr></table><br><br>
<br>
